ce:section.ce:para:
In our study, we also employed a theoretical approach to study the quenching effect in the carbon dots during metal ion sensing. Similarly to those of the metal-free C46 cluster, the S0 → S1 transitions of [C46–Li]+, [C46–Na]+, and [46-K]+ exhibited local excitation (Table 1
                        ). The excited electron-hole pair distances were zero, the electron-hole pair overlaps were high (>0.8), and no charge transfer occurred between C46 and the three metal ions during the transitions. The contributions of the Li+, Na+, and K+ ions to the excited electron and hole were almost zero. The NTOs of [C46–Li]+, [C46–Na]+, and [C46–K]+ also indicated that the excited electron and hole were completely located on C46 (Fig. 6
                        ). Accordingly, the π-π* transition and fluorescence emission process of C46 were not hindered by the coordination of Li+, Na+, or K+ to the C46 surface. These calculation results are consistent with the experimental observations, in which no quenching of 7BP-D was observed in the presence of Li+, Na+, or K+ ions (Fig. 5).
